Klimek & Wijay Family Lawyers is a premier family law firm and one of the largest in Western Australia practising exclusively in all areas of family law with respect to the breakdown of both matrimonial and de facto relationships (including same-sex relationships).

Unlike almost all family law firms in Western Australia it is:

1. an approved quality practice of the Law Society of Western Australia; and
2. able to provide highly experienced In-House Counsel, which ultimately serves to reduce the legal costs incurred by its clients should matters require litigation.

Legal services at the firm include:

 •    Divorce;
 •    De Facto Relationships;
 •    Child Support;
 •    Child and Parenting Matters;
 •    Spousal and Partner Maintenance;
 •    Binding Financial Agreements;
 •    Property Settlement; and
 •    Restraining Orders.

Its team includes seven well regarded family lawyers of considerable experience. They are each qualified barristers and solicitors who may appear in any Western Australian and Federal Court ranging from the Magistrates Courts and the Family Court of Western Australia to the Federal Magistrates Court and the Family Court of Australia, as well as their respective courts of appeal, including the High Court of Australia. Its team of family lawyers is ably assisted by skilled and committed paralegal, secretarial and administrative staff equipped with extensive resources, the latest technology and a well developed network of related services to which clients are referred for ancillary matters.

It represent clients based locally, interstate and internationally in matters ranging from those that are relatively uncomplicated to those that involve highly complex litigation requiring expert evidence and experienced advocacy.

The firm is also the Pro Bono Partner of the Northern Suburbs Community Legal Centre, to which we commit unpaid time on a weekly basis to provide advice and assistance to their clients with family law matters.

The Central Land Council (CLC) is an Australian Government statutory authority covering over 750,000 square kilometres in the southern half of the Northern Territory.

The CLC provides a number of services for the benefit of traditional owners and other Aboriginal residents of the CLC region. including:

- providing a strong voice for the Aboriginal people of Central Australia;
- helping Aboriginal people get back country;
- helping Aboriginal people manage their land;
- consulting with landowners on mining activity, employment, development and other land use proposals; 
- protecting Aboriginal culture and sacred sites;
-assisting with economic projects on Aboriginal land;
- promoting community development and improving service delivery;
- fighting for legal recognition of Aboriginal people's rights; and
- helping resolve land disputes, native title claims and compensation cases.

